          <LEXSenses>
            <LEXSense LanguageCode="en" LastEdited="2021-08-18 17:08:14" LastEditedBy="">
              <DefinitionLong/>
              <DefinitionShort>a particularly bitter herb with medicinal value</DefinitionShort>
              <Glosses>
                <Gloss>wormwood</Gloss>
              </Glosses>
              <Comments>In {S:06600801100016} it may be better to speak of the star as ‘bitterness,’ for example, ‘the name of the star is Bitter’ or ‘… Bitterness.’ It is, of course, also possible to speak of the star as ‘Bitter Plant’ or ‘Bitter Herb.’ A rendering of ἄψινθος as ‘wormy wood’ would be completely misleading and would provide no basis for understanding the second part of verse 11, for which see {D:79.43}. (The English term wormwood is derived from the use of the plant as a medicine to kill intestinal worms.)</Comments>
            </LEXSense>
          </LEXSenses>
